##European masks go missing, but nobody wears them on the street

The outbreak of the new coronavirus in European countries has yet to show signs of abating.

As of noon European time March 3, the most serious epidemic in Italy has reached a total of 2,063 confirmed cases, is the world's third largest affected country.

Due to the high mobility of the population brought about by European integration, except for some eastern European countries, almost all European countries have successively seen a large number of newly confirmed cases, among which France, Germany and Spain have the potential to break through the 200-case threshold, even Iceland, one of the hardest places to infect in the company's game, has nine confirmed cases.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The whole of Europe has fallen

Europe is already the worst affected region after three countries in East Asia and Iran, but unlike heavily armed Chinese cities, masks are still hard to find on the streets of European countries.

How much resistance is there in Europe to wearing masks?

In a prime example, on February 26th Matteo Dall'Osso, an Italian lawmaker, was ridiculed by his colleagues for wearing a mask to a meeting. Although Otho stressed to the speaker that the mask he was wearing did not affect anyone else and that it was just a precaution taken because he had previously been to an infected area in the north, but his move has drawn criticism on social media from many Italians who doubt his immune system is weak and deliberately consternation.

Not only in Italy, but also in the Canary Islands of Spain, a week ago, there was an emergency situation in which the H10 Costa Adeje Palace Hotel and nearly 1,000 of its guests were forcibly quarantined following the confirmation of a new coronavirus by a traveller.

Gu Zhen and his wife, who happened to be staying at the hotel, told me that although the local government had distributed masks to the quarantined people in the hotel, none of the other tourists on the island were wearing them. After the five-day quarantine ended, even the previously quarantined tourists took off their masks.

"All we saw from the hotel to the airport were two middle-aged white women wearing masks, and people were more concerned about whether the island's traffic would be blocked and whether they could leave the island on time than about the virus, " Gu said.

In Frankfurt, Germany's busiest train station, the author in half an hour can only find a German wearing a mask. But the man still chose to take off his mask when he was talking to others, simply because it was convenient to communicate.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
No one in the stands wore a mask during the Champions League quarter final against CLUBE ATLÉTICO Juventus on February 26, despite French complaints about the reception of more than 4,000 visitors.

Why are Europeans reluctant to wear masks? One important reason is that no European government or EU body has yet advised people to wear masks.

French Health Minister Olivier Veran has previously said publicly: "there is no need to wear a mask without a doctor's instruction, otherwise there will be a shortage of masks. " German Health Minister Jens Spann said: "wearing a mask is not necessary because the virus is not transmitted through inhalation. "

Even in Italy, where the situation is most dire, the health minister, Roberto Speranza, has published no guidelines for wearing a mask.

Indeed, the health ministers of Germany, France and Italy have never appeared in public wearing masks.

In addition to the official disapproval of wearing masks, there is debate in academia about the effectiveness of wearing masks.

Walter Ricciardi, an adviser to Italy's health minister, Speranza, and a member of the WHO's executive board, stressed that masks were only used to protect health care workers and patients. The team, including lead physician Clemens Wendtner, who previously used a adrenergic receptor agonist to slow and cure new cases of the German coronavirus, and the Robert Koch, where Germany's P4 lab is based, said: Wearing a mask in healthy people has little effect on preventing viral infections, and it is almost useless after 20 minutes of soaking.

There are plenty of ordinary Europeans who share this view.

"There is no evidence that wearing a mask is effective, ensuring your immunity and focusing on exercise, " Leonhart, an engineer at a BMW Munich supplier, told me on March 2, bMW's Munich research and development headquarters, Fiz, has been blocked because of the suspicion, but according to Leonhart, still no one chose to wear masks.

Another engineer in Frankfurt, Matthias, Holy Roman Emperor, also told me: "The working environment is almost young adults, the new coronavirus mortality rate is lower than the flu, there is no need to worry. "

Even Wovrowski, a salesman who works in high-traffic public spaces like Home Depot, scoffed at the new coronavirus. "there were a lot fewer customers today [ on Saturday ] , " he said. "I'm not sure it was the virus, but what's the big deal? More people die every year from flu than this,"he said, wovrowski also reminded me that another case had just been diagnosed nearby. Pressed on whether he was panicking, his only concern was that the outbreak would affect business this month.

Statistically, at least, the WOVROWSKIS are not entirely wrong. In Germany, at least, the flu kills between 100 and 200 people a year, according to the Robert Koch, and the new coronavirus has yet to die in Germany.

Even in Italy, where the death toll is more than 50, patients tend to be older and have a history of major illnesses.

In addition, most Europeans are convinced that "masks are for the sick" and the implicit discrimination that comes with it is also an important factor that makes wearing masks difficult to become a habit.

During the Leipzig Red bull-bayer Leverkusen match on March 1 in Leipzig, 20 Japanese players wearing masks and East Asian faces attracted the attention of security personnel, he was eventually forced off the pitch after 11 minutes.

Even inside a closed high-speed train carriage, wearing a mask is highly visible. I tried to put on a mask, but it quickly caused the crowd to whisper. Although no passengers will take the initiative to make comments, but because a week ago in Germany, passengers "reported" to train conductor suspected cases and forced to stop the entire high-speed train, I finally chose to give up wearing a mask.

On the other hand, while governments discourage the wearing of masks and the proportion of people wearing them on the street is extremely small, there is still a shortage of masks across Europe.

On March 1st the president of the European Commission, Francois von Der Leyen, confirmed that Italy had asked the European Union for help in supplying masks to the country.

But even in Germany, the country with the most production capacity, face masks have been snapped up in big pharmacies. It is understood that at present Bavaria and Frankfurt and other shops are unable to provide any disposable masks or N95 masks. As to when it will be possible to restock, "We can't be sure, " a munich-based pharmacy teller told me. "We can't even get through to the manufacturer's phone. The only place where there might be an inventory is the FFP3 masks in the building materials market. " FFP3 masks are euro-standard N95 masks, in general, only the paint spray workers will use.

According to the author on February 29 in the building materials market visit, the building materials market of various types of masks are still part of the spot, but the stock has also bottomed. "There are a lot of South Korean companies around here, and some South Koreans are snapping them up, " a construction worker who bought FFP3 masks for work told me, masks are still in stock in the building materials market only because the market is located far from the city, to avoid panic buying.

The scarcity of masks is most evident in the e-commerce platform represented by Amazon. It is understood that the most advanced FFP3 mask daily price of 10 euros / less. When I bought the mask in early February, the unit price had risen to 14 euros per unit, and there is even an individual seller on Amazon who has sold it for 90 euros per unit.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On the official website of Real supermarket in Germany, the price of FFP3 masks has risen to 999 euros (10 pieces) A box

Further exacerbating the scarcity of supplies and pushing up prices are Europeans'strict adherence to medical advice. Even the highest-rated FFP3 masks can not be used for more than three hours at a time, requiring a half-hour "rest period, " while the longest life of a single mask can not exceed 7.5 hours, pharmacy staff said. It also means that if a typical office worker is out for 10 hours a day, he or she will consume at least 40 masks a month.

But far scarcer than face masks are hand sanitizers, hand sanitizers and basic supplies, including pasta.

Although masks are not included in government guidelines, details such as "washing hands frequently, reducing handshakes and face stickers" have been mentioned repeatedly. The German Health Ministry has even advised people to hoard supplies at home for 10 days.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
At the March 2 meeting, the German Interior Minister rejected Merkl's handshake. Photograph: Daily Mirror

With official encouragement, supermarkets are running out of hygiene products, Pasta, bread, lunch meat and even peanuts.

According to my understanding, the most popular hand sanitizer and hand sanitizer in Amazon and other platforms and social networks have been sold to 100 euros per bottle. And individual sellers carry almost East Asian surnames.

Rewe, the German supermarket chain, also told me that "everything is being snapped up and not understood, " although the employee promised to restock shelves as soon as possible, but on the night of 2 March, Rewe cancelled all orders from Barilla, the pasta supplier, on the grounds that prices were rising.

There was a large shortage of Pasta at the Rewe supermarket counter. Photograph: Chen Ying
